  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13, 14) The writer concludes in his own fashion, freely modifying the older account to suit the needs of his contemporaries. (The Syriac and Arabic versions omit both verses.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) So the workmen wrought.—Literally, And the makers of the work made.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(13) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "So the workmen wrought.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "And the makers of the work made.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And the work was perfected by them.—Literally, and a bandage was applied to the work by their hand. This curious metaphor, expressive of restoration, is used again in a similar way in Nehemiah 4:1, “a bandage was applied to the walls of Jerusalem.” Jeremiah had used it before (Jeremiah 8:22; Jeremiah 30:17; comp. also Isaiah 58:8) of the national restoration.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And the work was perfected by them.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "and a bandage was applied to the work by their hand.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " This curious metaphor, expressive of restoration, is used again in a similar way in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 4:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", “a bandage was applied to the walls of Jerusalem.” Jeremiah had used it before (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 8:22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 30:17",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; comp. also ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 58:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") of the national restoration.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And they set the house of God in his state.—Rather, and they made the house of God to stand according to the measure thereof, i.e., in its original proportions. (Comp. Exodus 30:32 : màthkoneth, “measure,” “proportion.”) This verse is not read in Kings.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And they set the house of God in his state.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Rather, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "and they made the house of God to stand according to the measure thereof, i.e.,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " in its original proportions. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 30:32",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " : ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "màthkoneth, “",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "measure,” “proportion.”) This verse is not read in Kings.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Before the king and Jehoiada.—The expression appears to be characteristic of the present account. (Comp. Note on 2Chronicles 24:11.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Before the king and Jehoiada.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
